      <hedline>
        <hl1>Saving Social Security</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>James Roosevelt Jr letter backs Vice Pres Al Gore's proposals for saving Social Security system</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Safe Rescue for Social Security,'' by Donald B. Marron (Op-Ed, Oct. 12):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Safe Rescue for Social Security,'' by Donald B. Marron (Op-Ed, Oct. 12):</p>
        <p>Federal workers invest in their Thrift Savings Plan atop a solid foundation of Social Security as it is currently financed, as well as the Federal Employees Retirement System. That foundation would be seriously weakened by the withdrawal of 2 percentage points of the current 12.4 percent payroll tax, as Mr. Marron and George W. Bush propose.</p>
        <p>Al Gore's plan to pay down the publicly held debt and transfer the interest savings to the Social Security Trust Fund would extend its solvency to 2054 and allow some equity adjustments for elderly women. With small additional adjustments, the system could reach full 75-year solvency.</p>
        <p>Mr. Gore's plan would strengthen Social Security. That of Mr. Marron and Mr. Bush would hasten its demise and replace it with an erratic alternative.</p>
        <p>JAMES ROOSEVELT JR.  Cambridge, Mass., Oct. 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a former associate commissioner of Social Security for retirement policy.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
